				\begin{document}$\approx3$\end{document} days. The longitude of the Great Red Spot oscillated with a 90-day period (Link 1975; Reese and Beebe 1977). Why can such an ordered, stable, long-lived structure exist in the (randomly) turbulent atmosphere of a gas giant? Why would it not decay into similar turbulent structures as observed in the surroundings? There exists a similar feature in Neptune’s atmosphere, visible during 1989–1994, called the Great Dark Spot. Fig. 6
False-color image of the Great Red Spot of Jupiter, observed with Voyager [credit: NASA, Caltech/JPL—http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/releases/2002/release_2002_166.html]Fig. 7
