The chief competing theory for some years, applicable particularly to spiral in the past and to flocculent ones in Stochastic Self-Propagating Star Formation (SSPSF), but forward by Mueller and Arnett (1976) and further developed by Gerola and Seiden (1978). The idea is that a random fluctuation in gas density yields a small burst or star formation; winds from the stars and supernovae move outward, compressing gas, which, in turn, forms stars. Differential rotation in the disk, which will eventually wind up and spoil arms, in the short term (≈108\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
